<TITLE>CHAINS: Vu Gbe</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY LINK="#FF2400" VLINK="#5080FF"
 background="CHAINSImages/drumHeadTexture.JPG">

<CENTER><H1><I>Vu Gbe</I> -- Drum Language</H1></CENTER>

<P>
<table cellspacing=7><tr>
<td align=center><A HREF="video/vu15-60S.MOV"><IMG WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=149
   SRC="CHAINSImages/roundGbe.gif" border=0></A><br>
  <FONT SIZE=-2>
  Click on the image above to download a quicktime movie of
  Francis speaking and playing drum language at the Anyako
  performance. (2.3MB)</FONT></td>
<td>In <I>Eve, vu</I>, drum, <I>gbe</I>, voice, <I>vu gbe</I>, what is
said with the voice of drums; in other words, drum language.  In
Ghana, the Eve people are masters of the coded messages of drum
language.  Drum language is also a cultural mainstay of Ashanti,
Dagomba, Ga peoples in Ghana, and other West African ethnic groups
such as the Fon in Benin and the Yoruba in Nigeria.  Because their
language is tonal, the drums can act as a speech surrogate with the
low, high and middle tones mimicing the tonal patterns of the spoken
language.  Master drummers can use drums to reach people on a
deeper level. <p>
This performance,
<a href="index.html">Coded Messages: CHAINS</a>, was built as a series of
new interpretations of a single passage of drum language from the
traditional Eve dance, Adzogbo.  You can hear it in different languages here.
</table>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=-2>Click the icons below to hear drum language from
<A HREF="adzogbo.html">Adzogbo</A>
and its meaning in Eve and English.</font></center>

<TABLE BORDER WIDTH="100%" CELLPADDING=10 CELLSPACING=10>

